intro:
Good morning / afternoon. I'm Kailash Narayan Kiradu, a Computer Science graduate from RMK Engineering College, Chennai.
Over the last few months, I worked as a Java Full-Stack Engineer Intern at Cognizant, where I architected AcquirerX, a microservices-based merchant acquiring and POS switch platform. It spans about twelve domain microservices covering the full payment lifecycle, from merchant onboarding to settlement and dispute workflows. I built it using Spring Boot, Spring Cloud, and React, with patterns like JWT-based role access, Resilience4J circuit breakers, and Swagger documentation. That internship gave me real exposure to how enterprise systems are designed and shipped.
Before Cognizant, I worked on my final-year project, Care++, an AI-driven clinical decision-support system. It brings together CNN-based medical image analysis, BioBERT for biomedical entity recognition, and LLM-powered clinical summarization, all running on a hybrid Python and Spring Boot microservices stack. The research from this project was published as an IEEE paper.
Earlier, I interned at ITC Limited as a Software Development Intern, where I built a real-time log monitoring solution using Grafana, Prometheus, and Loki across five production servers. That was my first taste of how observability really matters in production systems.
Right now, I'm extending my full-stack foundation into AI-native engineering. I'm actively building expertise in RAG pipelines, LangChain, vector retrieval, and prompt engineering, because I see that as the direction the industry is moving in, especially for enterprise applications.
What draws me to the Cognizant Ace Team specifically is the chance to combine my full-stack engineering background with the AI-native work that the role focuses on. I'd love to walk you through any of these projects in more depth.


